title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant 9130 - 1939 Tula
location: Otsego County, Northern Lower Peninsula, Michigan
postcontent:
For sale is a very nice Russian Mosin Nagant manufactured at the Tula Arsenal in 1939.  This is a refurbished rifle - probably in the Ukraine as noted by the markings on the butt stock.  This is a numbers matching rifle which means the barrel, bolt, magazine and butt plate serial numbers are matched.  The magazine, as with many, was force matched during the refurbishment process as noted by the "line out" of the old serial number and the restamping of the new one.  The rifle has an excellent, like new, bore, is not counter-bored and has an excellent crown.  The stock has some chipping of the shellac and some scratches, but nothing serious and does not detract from the overall appearance of the rifle. The stock has many interesting cartouches as well.  This rifle has been meticulously cleaned and maintained in a low humidity environment. The rifle has no rust. Firing pin protrusion has been set and headspace is perfect. The firing chamber is immaculate and chambers/extracts rounds easily.  The trigger is very crisp for a Russian 9130. There is no residual cosmoline (axle grease) on this rifle, although the stock may "sweat" a little in the sun.

Overall this is a very nice example of the Mosin Nagant 3-line rifle and is ready to shoot right out of the box. As with all used firearms, however, the buyer should ensure safety by having a licensed gunsmith inspect the rifle prior to shooting.

I will include a bayonet (non matching), a couple ammo pouches, a sling, an oil can and cleaning kit if you desire.  If FTF transaction, I will throw in 20 rounds of ammo free.

Purchase requirements:

I prefer a face to face meeting within the State of Michigan but will ship at the buyer's  expense.  I WILL NOT ship out of the state of Michigan without first receiving payment and a signed copy of the transferee's FFL. C&R is ok. It is the buyer's responsibility to know if this rifle is legal to purchase in their state.

I WILL NOT ship within the State of Michigan unless first receiving payment.  Unfortunately, I will have to ship to an FFL and would need a copy of that license prior to shipping.

Payment:

Payment can be made via PayPal (gift to friends and family), personal check, POSTAL Money Order if shipped. Note, that I have to ensure a personal check clears prior to shipping.  That could take up to a week.  If FTF, cash is required.  If you want additional pictures, I will be happy to send them to you.  Thank you for looking.

title: For Sale:  Ultimak M1-B AK Rail System
postcontent:
I have a like new Ultimak AK Gas Tube Rail System.  I mounted this on my AK and decided to go a different route.

UltiMAK M1-B optic mount. Its Picatinny style rail is positioned well below the iron sight axis, making this the lowest optic mount available for the AK. With a tubular sight mounted low, you will be able to use your optic without a comb riser and still use your regular hold. The system allows for co witnessing (the ability to use your iron sights right through a 1x sight as a back-up sighting system) when used with a tubular reflex sight. This heavy duty mount replaces the original steel gas tube and upper handguard, so it adds less than one ounce to the weight of the rifle, making it by far the lightest optic mount installation in the world. The forward positioning of the optic gives you faster, easier and more natural targeting while maintaining your full field of view. Multiple target or moving target engagements, with both eyes open, become second nature.

German Mauser K98 for sale. In collector-grade condition, beautiful rifle, all german/nazi markings intact, clean bore, nice wood, action is in superb condition.
Bought it many years ago, have never fired it - it has been sitting idle on my safe and I need to sell it as I have some financial obligations to fulfill.
This is a 1936 military production Mauser 98K rifle, the top of the receiver is marked "S/42" which is the wartime code for the Mauser factory at Oberndorf and "1936" which signifies the year of manufacture. The right side of the receiver has three "eagle/63" proofmarks, the left side has the eagle firing proof and serial number, and the left side wall is marked "Mod.98". The left rear of the barrel has the firing proof and matching serial number and the right side directly behind the hand guard is marked with two "Eagle/WaA63" proofs. It has the early all milled components, blade front sight and tangent rear sight graduated to 2,000 meters.
Also, I have a tin can of 7.92mm rounds (350 rounds) to go with the rifle. 
This is likely a Russian-captured rifle in excellent condition, a nice piece of history to say the least.
